Michael,

Cantera is telling you that the thermo for your species &#39;c7h15o-1=
&#39; is inconsistent.

The problem is in your cti file (or, technically, in th=
e heptane_symp.therm chemkin file you&#39;re using to create the cti file).  It=
 looks like you&#39;re using a NASA polynomial for your thermo, in which case c=
antera is calculating standard Cp, h, and s values based on the following e=
quations:

Cp0/R =3D a1 + a2*T + a3*T^2 + a4*T^3 + a5*T^4

h0/R =3D a1*T + =
a2/2*T^2 + a3/3*T^3 + a4/4*T^4 + a5/5*T^5 + a6

s0/R =3D a1*ln(T) + a2*T + =
a3/2*T^2 + a4/3*T^3 + a5/4T^4 + a7

with a different set of a-values for lo=
w T ( below 1391, in your case) and high T.  However, when Cantera uses T =
=3D 1391, it should be able to get the same values for Cp0, h0, and s0 whet=
her it uses the low-T or the high-T parameters.  In your case, it isn&#39;t, wh=
ich is causing the warning/error.  You can find more info on this in the &#39;d=
efiningphases.pdf&#39; file in Cantera&#39;s documentation, I believe.

The easiest=
 way to resolve this would be to open up the cti file created by ck2cti (it=
 should be in the &#39;Cantera&#92;Data&#39; folder) and do a ctrl + f search for &quot;c7h1=
5o-1&quot; (it&#39;s about 80% of the way down the page in your therm file).  

The =
discrepancies aren&#39;t too large, so you could put the expressions and parame=
ters into any mathematical software (matlab, excel, etc) and adjust the par=
ameters manually so that the three values are equal at 1391 from above and =
below.  If there&#39;s a temperature range (high or low) that is less pertinent=
 to you, I&#39;d pick those parameters to adjust--I would start with a1, to mak=
e Cp0 match, and then adjust a6 and a7 to make h0 and s0 match, respectivel=
y.

Fixing the &#39;therm&#39; file and them reconverting with ck2cti would be equi=
valent, if you&#39;d rather do that.

I hope this helps, and that I&#39;ve correctl=
y understood your problem.

Regards,
Steven


